<meta itemprop="description" content="Viśvāvasumati (विश्वावसुमति).—A Marut gaṇa.** Matsya-purāṇa 171. 53.">


<h2 class="mb-3" id="introduction">Introduction:</h2><p><span itemprop="name">Vishvavasumati</span> means something in <a href="/hinduism">Hinduism</a>, Sanskrit. If you want to know the exact meaning, history, etymology or English translation of this term then check out the descriptions on this page. Add your comment or reference to a book if you want to contribute to this summary article. </p>
</div>
<p>The Sanskrit term Viśvāvasumati can be transliterated into English as Visvavasumati or Vishvavasumati, using the IAST transliteration scheme <a href="Javascript:void(0)" title="IAST stands for International Alphabet of Sanskrit Transliteration">(?)</a>.</p><div class="spacer"></div><h2 style="margin-top: 26px;" class="bookSubHeader" id="hinduism">In Hinduism</h2><h3 id="purana">Purana and Itihasa (epic history)</h3> 
<div class="row justify-content-between cat-toolbar">

<div class="col-12 col-md-auto" itemscope itemtype="https://schema.org/DefinedTermSet">
